  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Ambulatory 24-hour esophageal pH monitoring is the standard for diagnosing GERD. This test involves placing a pH probe transnasally 5 cm above the manometrically determined upper border of the lower esophageal sphincter (LES). The test quantifies the frequency and duration of acid reflux episodes during a 24-hour period, allowing correlation with the patient's symptoms. Combined multichannel intraluminal impedance-pH monitoring improves the diagnostic yield by detecting non-acid reflux events in addition to acid reflux. This is particularly valuable in evaluating patients with persistent symptoms despite acid-suppressive therapy. Esophageal pH testing is indicated for patients with persistent symptoms despite PPI therapy, for those with atypical symptoms in whom GERD is suspected, and prior to consideration of endoscopic or surgical antireflux procedures.",
