  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Non-ST-segment elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI) is characterized by ST-segment depression or T-wave inversion on ECG and elevated cardiac biomarkers (troponin or CK-MB). The initial medical management includes antiplatelet therapy (aspirin plus a P2Y12 inhibitor), anticoagulant therapy (heparin or low-molecular-weight heparin), beta-blockers, and statins. Early invasive strategy with coronary angiography and revascularization is recommended for high-risk patients, those with recurrent ischemia, heart failure, hemodynamic instability, or sustained ventricular arrhythmias. Percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) is the preferred revascularization strategy for patients with single-vessel disease, while coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG) is generally preferred for patients with left main coronary artery disease, three-vessel disease, or two-vessel disease with proximal left anterior descending artery involvement, especially in those with diabetes or left ventricular dysfunction.",
