  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Computed tomographic pulmonary angiography (CTPA) is the imaging modality of choice for diagnosing pulmonary embolism (PE). It allows direct visualization of pulmonary arterial filling defects and provides information about alternative diagnoses if PE is absent. CTPA has high sensitivity (83-100%) and specificity (89-97%) for the diagnosis of PE. In patients with suspected PE and an elevated D-dimer level, CTPA is the next appropriate diagnostic step. The test can detect emboli in segmental and larger pulmonary arteries with high accuracy. Additionally, CTPA can provide information about the burden of emboli, the presence of right ventricular strain, and other lung pathologies that may explain the patient's symptoms.",
