  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: Musculoskeletal chest pain, also known as chest wall syndrome, is one of the most common causes of noncardiac chest pain. It is characterized by localized chest pain that is reproducible by palpation of the affected area, often exacerbated by movement or breathing, and may be associated with localized tenderness. Common sites include the costochondral and chondrosternal junctions, intercostal muscles, and the pectoral muscles. The pain is typically sharp, well-localized, and of brief duration, though it can persist for hours or days. It may be precipitated by physical activity, stress, or minor trauma. The diagnosis is primarily clinical, based on the characteristic features of the pain and the absence of findings suggesting cardiac, pulmonary, or gastrointestinal disease. The presence of reproducible chest wall tenderness has a high positive predictive value for a musculoskeletal etiology.",
